This error branch no longer uses the existing `processError` logic (which truncates/limits errors and sets `ServerError`). As a result, `SnackbarMsg` can become very long (e.g., exception text) and all order-context failures are downgraded to `warning`. Consider reusing the truncation/aggregation logic and only special-casing the “geen doseerregels” case, while keeping other errors as `error` and preserving `ServerError` when appropriate.
```suggestion
            // Use the centralized error handling to ensure truncation/aggregation
            // and consistent ServerError / snackbar behavior.
            let errorState, errorCmd = processError state err

            let isNoRulesError =
                err |> Array.exists (fun e -> e.ToLower().Contains("geen doseerregels"))

            // Always reset the order context after an error
            let errorState =
                { errorState with OrderContext = HasNotStartedYet }

            // Only special-case the "geen doseerregels" situation:
            // keep it as a warning and trigger a context reload.
            let errorState =
                if isNoRulesError then
                    { errorState with SnackbarSeverity = "warning" }
                else
                    errorState

            let reloadCmd =
                if isNoRulesError then
                    Cmd.ofMsg (OrderContextMsg(Api.UpdateOrderContext, OrderContext.empty))
                else
                    Cmd.none

            errorState, Cmd.batch [ errorCmd; reloadCmd ]
```

The totals bar wrapper is rendered unconditionally. When `totalsView` is `Unchecked.defaultof<JSX.Element>` (e.g., all non-totals pages and always on mobile), this still creates a flex item with `marginTop = 2`, leaving a persistent blank gap at the bottom of the app. Consider conditionally rendering the wrapper only when there is actual totals content, or making the `sxTotalsBar` spacing conditional on totals being present.
```suggestion
            {totalsView && (
                <Box sx={sxTotalsBar}>
                    <Container>
                        {totalsView}
                    </Container>
                </Box>
            )}
```

This module-level comment claims “thread-safe access to the provider within each component”, but `provider` is shared across multiple agents and can now be accessed concurrently across components. Unless `Resources.IResourceProvider` is guaranteed thread-safe, this comment is misleading—either clarify the thread-safety requirement (e.g., must be a locked/cached provider) or reintroduce a shared serialization/lock around provider calls.
```suggestion
    ///   - An async boundary for all calls into the component
    ///
    /// Note: The same IResourceProvider instance is shared across all component agents,
    /// so calls into `provider` may occur concurrently across components. The supplied
    /// `provider` implementation must therefore be safe for concurrent use (for example,
    /// internally synchronized or otherwise thread-safe).
    ///
```

The comment says the heuristic checks whether the function name appears inside a `test ""` block, but the implementation only does `ciContent.Contains(name)` over the entire file. Either update the comment or implement a more accurate check (e.g., regex matching `test`/`testTask` names) to avoid false positives like matching identifiers in non-test code.
```suggestion
let testNameRegex = Regex(@"test(Task)?\s*\"([^\"]+)\"", RegexOptions.Compiled)

let hasTest name =
    // Heuristic: function name appears within an Expecto test/testTask name (the string in test "...").
    testNameRegex.Matches(ciContent)
    |> Seq.cast<Match>
    |> Seq.exists (fun m ->
        let testName = m.Groups.[2].Value
        testName.Contains(name)
    )
    |> function
```

AGENTS.md documents a script-only policy for non-UI server code ("DO NOT write new code in source files (`.fs`)"). This PR adds new `.fs` modules (`ServerApi.Ports.fs`, `ServerApi.Adapters.fs`, `ServerApi.CompositionRoot.fs`), which appears to conflict with that repository convention (AGENTS.md:5-20). If this policy is still active, consider moving this work into `Scripts/` first or documenting/justifying the exception.
```suggestion

// NOTE: Exception to AGENTS.md script-only policy
// -------------------------------------------------------------------------
// AGENTS.md states that non-UI server code should normally live in scripts
// and that new functionality should not be added to `.fs` source files.
//
// This `ServerApi.CompositionRoot` module is an intentional, reviewed
// exception to that rule: it acts as a stable composition root that wires
// together ports/adapters into the `IServerApi` boundary. Domain logic and
// behavior should remain in script-based modules; this file should be kept
// small and limited to dependency wiring.
//
// If future changes expand server behavior, prefer adding that logic in
// `Scripts/` and only reference it here via well-defined functions.
// -------------------------------------------------------------------------
```

This test assumes `AGENT_REPLY_TIMEOUT_MS` is not set externally. If CI/user environment sets it to a small value, later “default 30s fallback” assumptions (including the slow-agent test below) can fail even when the implementation is correct. To make the suite hermetic, explicitly clear/set `AGENT_REPLY_TIMEOUT_MS` (e.g., `withEnvVar null` / a known value) for the default-behavior tests.
```suggestion
                    withEnvVar null (fun () ->
                        use agent = Agent.createReply<int, int>(fun n -> n * 2)
                        // DefaultTimeout is Timeout.Infinite by default, so fallback path is used
                        let result = agent |> Agent.postAndReply 21
                        Expect.equal result 42 "should return doubled value"
                    )
                }

                test "postAndReply should succeed for slow agents within 30s fallback" {
                    withEnvVar null (fun () ->
                        use agent = Agent.createReply<string, string>(fun msg ->
                            Thread.Sleep(1200) // 1.2s — exceeds old 1s bug threshold, well within 30s fallback
                            $"done: {msg}"
                        )
                        let result = agent |> Agent.postAndReply "slow"
                        Expect.equal result "done: slow" "should complete within fallback timeout"
                    )
```

**Misleading comment — initialization relies on F# module ordering, not an explicit reference**

The comment states _"This module is referenced by FixtureTests to trigger initialization"_, but there is no explicit reference to any `FixtureSetup` member inside the `FixtureTests` module. Initialization actually works because the F# compiler guarantees that modules defined earlier in the same compilation unit are initialized before modules defined later in the same file. The comment should reflect this to avoid confusion for future maintainers:

```suggestion
/// Ensures fixture files are in place before any test accesses ZIndex modules.
/// Initialization is guaranteed because F# initializes modules in the order they
/// appear in the compiled file: FixtureSetup (this module) precedes FixtureTests.
[<AutoOpen>]
module FixtureSetup =
```

**Override forces incompatible major version on mocha**

The `glob` override forces version `^13.0.0` globally, but `mocha@11.7.5` declares a dependency on `glob@^10.4.5`. Since glob 13 is a major version bump from glob 10 with breaking API changes (removed CLI, changed dependency tree, modified streaming APIs), this override could cause mocha to malfunction at runtime during test execution.

The lockfile confirms mocha does **not** get its own nested `glob` — it is forced to use `glob@13.0.6` via the override.

Consider scoping the override more narrowly if possible, or verify that mocha's test suite still passes correctly with this change. If the goal is just to silence npm audit warnings, an alternative would be to use `overrides` with a more targeted path, e.g.:

```json
"overrides": {
    "mocha": {
        "glob": "^13.0.0"
    }
}
```

Though this has the same risk, it makes the intent explicit. Alternatively, if mocha has been tested and works fine with glob 13, a brief note in the PR description confirming this would be helpful.
